me it's a slam dunk.

984
00:58:42,953 --> 00:58:45,899
<i>Well, congratulations Jeffrey.</i>

985
00:58:45,923 --> 00:58:48,991
Anything else on your plate?

986
00:58:49,159 --> 00:58:51,059
Not really.

987
00:58:51,228 --> 00:58:55,964
<i>Feel like sharing?</i>

988
00:58:56,133 --> 00:59:00,802
I've got this student in my
introductory class this semester

989
00:59:00,971 --> 00:59:03,572
who's... well, he's
taken a challenge

990
00:59:03,741 --> 00:59:06,542
to prove the existence of God.

991
00:59:06,710 --> 00:59:08,043
In your classroom?

992
00:59:08,211 --> 00:59:11,013
- Yes.
- Silly boy.

993
00:59:11,181 --> 00:59:13,248
- Freshman?
- Oh yeah.

994
00:59:13,617 --> 00:59:15,695
Doesn't seem quite fair to me.

995
00:59:15,719 --> 00:59:17,052
Well, how's that?

996
00:59:18,321 --> 00:59:20,166
<i>He's inexperienced
in front of a room,</i>

997
00:59:20,190 --> 00:59:21,935
and you're expecting
him to compete with you

998
00:59:21,959 --> 00:59:24,103
<i>in your own field of expertise.</i>

999
00:59:24,127 --> 00:59:26,272
<i>Come on, Mina.
This is fun for me.</i>

1000
00:59:26,296 --> 00:59:28,207
I can't help it if a boy wants
to make a fool of himself

1001
00:59:28,231 --> 00:59:30,165
and commit academic suicide.

1002
00:59:30,333 --> 00:59:31,867
<i>Look, I tried to stop him.</i>

1003
00:59:32,036 --> 00:59:33,880
I gave him an
out, but no, no, no,

1004
00:59:33,904 --> 00:59:36,572
he wants to prove
that God isn't dead.

1005
00:59:38,776 --> 00:59:42,711
Look, I know I am
in the minority here,

1006
00:59:42,880 --> 00:59:45,681
but I actually believe in God.

1007
00:59:51,188 --> 00:59:54,856
Yes, yes, well, she is...
She's a work in progress.

1008
00:59:57,661 --> 00:59:59,773
<i>So, darling, I think it's best
we just change the subject.</i>

1009
00:59:59,797 --> 01:00:01,074
<i>But I'm just saying...</i>

1010
01:00:01,098 --> 01:00:04,700
Mina, I've asked politely, okay?

1011
01:00:06,770 --> 01:00:08,269
Okay.

1012
01:00:10,240 --> 01:00:11,918
The coq au vin is almost done.

1013
01:00:11,942 --> 01:00:13,709
<i>Excellent.</i>

1014
01:00:13,877 --> 01:00:15,644
To the dining room.

1015
01:00:54,051 --> 01:00:57,211
<i>Nothing like a nice
merlot to take the edge off.</i>

1016
01:00:59,923 --> 01:01:02,357
Cheers, everyone.

1017
01:01:05,729 --> 01:01:07,328
Mina, this wine is awful.

1018
01:01:07,497 --> 01:01:09,031
It's been cooked.

1019
01:01:09,199 --> 01:01:12,067
It tastes like it was sunning
in a moldy basement.

1020
01:01:12,235 --> 01:01:14,115
Talk about your
"Grapes of Wrath."

1021
01:01:19,943 --> 01:01:22,844
I bought it before I went
shopping the other day.

1022
01:01:23,013 --> 01:01:25,914
I locked it in the trunk

1023
01:01:26,083 --> 01:01:28,850
and when I got
home I forgot about it.

1024
01:01:29,019 --> 01:01:32,420
Well, I think this dinner
serves as a valuable lesson.

1025
01:01:32,790 --> 01:01:35,090
<i>As Socrates put it
over 2,000 years ago,</i>

1026
01:01:35,258 --> 01:01:38,060
"Gnothi seauton."

1027
01:01:40,998 --> 01:01:43,364
Looks like it's Greek to her.

1028
01:01:43,533 --> 01:01:46,702
<i>Oh, it's "Know thyself,"
darling, know thyself.</i>

1029
01:01:46,870 --> 01:01:52,107
Which I suggest means
knowing your own limitations.

1030
01:02:00,084 --> 01:02:05,020
You know, if you'll
all excuse me,

1031
01:02:05,189 --> 01:02:08,123
it's time for the
help to depart.

1032
01:02:08,291 --> 01:02:10,158
Sweetheart...

1033
01:02:12,362 --> 01:02:20,362
♪♪♪

1034
01:02:27,377 --> 01:02:35,377
♪♪♪

1035
01:02:41,125 --> 01:02:42,965
<i>No pacemaker?</i>

1036
01:02:43,093 --> 01:02:46,228
<i>No other piercings, right?</i>

1037
01:02:46,396 --> 01:02:47,929
No.

1038
01:02:49,366 --> 01:02:51,644
<i>I know it sounds
crazy, but I have to ask.</i>

1039
01:02:51,668 --> 01:02:53,412
<i>If there's any ferrous metal
anywhere inside your body,</i>

1040
01:02:53,436 --> 01:02:56,138
<i>the magnetic field will
put it out, and forcibly.</i>

1041
01:02:56,473 --> 01:03:04,473
♪♪♪

1042
01:03:05,548 --> 01:03:07,560
<i>In our last class, I
was asked a question</i>

1043
01:03:07,584 --> 01:03:10,252
<i>that I couldn't answer.</i>

1044
01:03:10,420 --> 01:03:12,921
<i>As Professor
Radisson pointed out,</i>

1045
01:03:13,090 --> 01:03:15,023
<i>Stephen Hawking is an atheist.</i>

1046
01:03:15,192 --> 01:03:17,036
<i>He also wrote a book
called "The Grand Design"</i>

1047
01:03:17,060 --> 01:03:21,562
<i>in which he says the following:</i>

1048
01:03:21,932 --> 01:03:24,032
<i>"Because there is a
law such as gravity,</i>

1049
01:03:24,201 --> 01:03:28,503
<i>the universe can and will
create itself from nothing."</i>

1050
01:03:28,872 --> 01:03:32,274
And to be honest, I didn't
know how to refute that.

1051
01:03:32,442 --> 01:03:39,281
I mean, after all, Hawking
is clearly a genius.

1052
01:03:39,449 --> 01:03:42,017
But, Professor John Lennox,

1053
01:03:42,186 --> 01:03:43,863
who teaches mathematics
and philosophy

1054
01:03:43,887 --> 01:03:46,487
<i>has demonstrated that
there are not one, even two,</i>

1055
01:03:46,656 --> 01:03:48,990
but three errors
of logic contained

1056
01:03:49,159 --> 01:03:50,525
<i>in that one simple sentence,</i>

1057
01:03:50,894 --> 01:03:54,395
and it all boils down
to circular reasoning.

1058
01:03:54,564 --> 01:03:57,232
<i>Hawking is basically saying
that the universe exists</i>

1059
01:03:57,400 --> 01:03:59,534
<i>because the universe
needed to exist,</i>

1060
01:03:59,903 --> 01:04:01,380
and because the
universe needed to exist,

1061
01:04:01,404 --> 01:04:04,306
it therefore created itself.

1062
01:04:04,474 --> 01:04:06,007
<i>It's like this.</i>

1063
01:04:06,176 --> 01:04:08,021
If I say to you that I can prove

1064
01:04:08,045 --> 01:04:10,123
that Spam is the best-tasting
food that's ever existed

1065
01:04:10,147 --> 01:04:13,448
because in all of history, no
food has ever tasted better,

1066
01:04:13,616 --> 01:04:15,295
you'd probably
look at me strange

1067
01:04:15,319 --> 01:04:16,996
and say I haven't
proven anything.

1068
01:04:17,020 --> 01:04:18,353
And you'd be right,

1069
01:04:18,521 --> 01:04:20,621
all I've done is restate
my original claim.

1070
01:04:20,991 --> 01:04:22,969
<i>But when Hawking claims
that the universe created itself</i>

1071
01:04:22,993 --> 01:04:25,126
<i>because it needed
to create itself,</i>

1072
01:04:25,295 --> 01:04:27,255
and then offers that
as an explanation

1073
01:04:27,331 --> 01:04:29,397
as to how and
why it was created,

1074
01:04:29,566 --> 01:04:32,901
we don't immediately recognize
that he's doing the same thing.

1075
01:04:33,070 --> 01:04:36,204
But he is, prompting
Lennox to further comment,

1076
01:04:36,373 --> 01:04:37,939
<i>"Nonsense remains nonsense,</i>

1077
01:04:38,108 --> 01:04:40,876
<i>"even when spoken
by famous scientists</i>

1078
01:04:41,044 --> 01:04:42,555
<i>"even though the general public</i>

1079
01:04:42,579 --> 01:04:44,257
<i>assumes they are
statements of science."</i>

1080
01:04:44,281 --> 01:04:45,881
This is the height of hubris.

1081
01:04:46,049 --> 01:04:47,526
<i>Are you telling me
that you, a freshman,</i>

1082
01:04:47,550 --> 01:04:49,450
are saying that Stephen
Hawking is wrong?

1083
01:04:49,619 --> 01:04:52,921
No, what I'm saying
is that John Lennox,

1084
01:04:53,090 --> 01:04:55,050
<i>a professor of
mathematics and philosophy,</i>

1085
01:04:55,658 --> 01:04:57,203
<i>has found Professor
Hawking's reasoning to be faulty,</i>

1086
01:04:57,227 --> 01:04:58,393
and I agree with his logic.

1087
01:04:59,263 --> 01:05:01,129
<i>But if you can't
bear to disagree</i>

1088
01:05:01,298 --> 01:05:02,630
with Hawking's thinking,

1089
01:05:03,000 --> 01:05:05,200
then I suggest that you
turn to page five of his book,

1090
01:05:05,369 --> 01:05:09,237
where he insists
philosophy is dead.

1091
01:05:10,140 --> 01:05:11,639
<i>And if you're so sure</i>

1092
01:05:12,009 --> 01:05:13,486
of Professor
Hawking's infallibility,

1093
01:05:13,510 --> 01:05:15,188
and philosophy really is dead,

1094
01:05:15,212 --> 01:05:21,082
then well, there's really
no need for this class.

1095
01:05:24,521 --> 01:05:28,423
<i>It's like I'm a
convenience to him,</i>

1096
01:05:28,591 --> 01:05:31,226
<i>except for when
my faith comes up,</i>

1097
01:05:31,395 --> 01:05:33,506
then he becomes
verbally abusive.

1098
01:05:33,530 --> 01:05:35,563
I'm guessing he's bright.

1099
01:05:35,732 --> 01:05:37,265
Brilliant.

1100
01:05:37,434 --> 01:05:39,034
Handsome.

1101
01:05:39,202 --> 01:05:40,535
Yes.

1102
01:05:40,703 --> 01:05:43,271
And his attention
makes you feel special,

1103
01:05:43,440 --> 01:05:45,673
gives you a sense
of completeness.

1104
01:05:46,043 --> 01:05:48,443
Have you been reading my diary?

1105
01:05:48,511 --> 01:05:51,046
Psychologists call it
the Cinderella complex.

1106
01:05:51,214 --> 01:05:54,015
It's not my name for it,
so don't get upset with me.

1107
01:05:54,184 --> 01:05:55,544
Guys are capable
of the same thing.

1108
01:05:55,585 --> 01:05:57,618
It's just they don't
have a name for it.

1109
01:05:57,787 --> 01:05:59,532
But in essence, you're
looking for his approval

1110
01:05:59,556 --> 01:06:01,056
to give you a
sense of self-worth

1111
01:06:01,224 --> 01:06:03,258
instead of generating
it internally.

1112
01:06:03,427 --> 01:06:05,126
Don't most people do that?

1113
01:06:05,295 --> 01:06:07,595
Yeah, a lot of people do, sure.

1114
01:06:07,764 --> 01:06:09,464
But, using romance
to shore up self-image

1115
01:06:09,632 --> 01:06:12,367
is an unstable foundation.

1116
01:06:12,535 --> 01:06:15,736
Do you believe God's capable
of error, bias, or bad judgment?

1117
01:06:16,106 --> 01:06:17,439
No.

1118
01:06:17,607 --> 01:06:20,375
So, if he's incapable
of mistakes,

1119
01:06:20,543 --> 01:06:24,545
and he made you in
his likeness and image,

1120
01:06:24,714 --> 01:06:27,315
then it follows that he
cares about you, right?

1121
01:06:27,484 --> 01:06:29,250
Right.

1122
01:06:29,419 --> 01:06:30,986
To the point where
God's only Son

1123
01:06:31,154 --> 01:06:35,457
would willingly be crucified
again for you, just you,

1124
01:06:35,625 --> 01:06:37,492
if that's what was necessary.

1125
01:06:37,660 --> 01:06:40,261
Well, if he loves you that much,

1126
01:06:40,430 --> 01:06:44,665
who cares what
your boyfriend thinks?

1127
01:06:44,834 --> 01:06:50,571
To the wrong person,
you'll never have any worth.

1128
01:06:50,740 --> 01:06:57,512
But to the right person,
you'll mean everything.

1129
01:07:01,818 --> 01:07:04,386
<i>Ladies and
gentlemen of the jury,</i>

1130
01:07:04,554 --> 01:07:07,622
for the last 150 years,
Darwinists have been saying

1131
01:07:07,790 --> 01:07:10,492
that God is unnecessary
to explain man's existence

1132
01:07:10,660 --> 01:07:13,161
<i>and that evolution replaces God,</i>

1133
01:07:13,330 --> 01:07:15,375
<i>but evolution only
tells you what happens</i>

1134
01:07:15,399 --> 01:07:17,165
<i>once you have life.</i>

1135
01:07:17,334 --> 01:07:19,612
<i>So, where did that something
that's alive come from?</i>

1136
01:07:19,636 --> 01:07:21,702
Well, Darwin never
really addressed it.

1137
01:07:21,871 --> 01:07:24,205
He assumed maybe some
lightning hit a stagnant pool

1138
01:07:24,374 --> 01:07:25,851
full of the right
kind of chemicals

1139
01:07:25,875 --> 01:07:28,410
and bingo, a living something.

1140
01:07:28,578 --> 01:07:31,146
But it's just not that simple.

1141
01:07:31,314 --> 01:07:34,382
<i>You see, Darwin claimed that
the ancestry of all living things</i>

1142
01:07:34,551 --> 01:07:37,718
<i>came from that one
single, simple organism</i>

1143
01:07:37,887 --> 01:07:40,355
which reproduced and was
slowly modified over time

1144
01:07:40,524 --> 01:07:42,657
<i>into the complex life
forms we view today.</i>

1145
01:07:42,825 --> 01:07:45,626
Which is why, after
contemplating his own theory,

1146
01:07:45,795 --> 01:07:48,263
Darwin uttered his
famous statement,

1147
01:07:48,432 --> 01:07:50,231
"Natura non facit saltum,"

1148
01:07:50,400 --> 01:07:55,603
<i>meaning, "Nature does not jump."</i>

1149
01:07:55,772 --> 01:07:57,972
<i>Well, as noted author
Lee Strobel pointed out,</i>

1150
01:07:58,141 --> 01:08:01,176
that if you can picture
the entire 3.8 billion years

1151
01:08:01,344 --> 01:08:03,464
<i>that scientists say
life has been around</i>

1152
01:08:03,547 --> 01:08:05,113
<i>as one 24-hour day,</i>

1153
01:08:05,282 --> 01:08:07,648
<i>in the space of just
about 90 seconds,</i>

1154
01:08:07,817 --> 01:08:09,817
<i>most major animal
groups suddenly appear</i>

1155
01:08:10,187 --> 01:08:11,664
<i>in the forms in which
they currently hold.</i>

1156
01:08:11,688 --> 01:08:14,155
<i>Not slowly and steadily
as Darwin predicted,</i>

1157
01:08:14,324 --> 01:08:18,659
but in evolutionary
terms, almost instantly.

1158
01:08:18,828 --> 01:08:21,829
So, "nature does
not jump" becomes

1159
01:08:22,199 --> 01:08:25,766
<i>"nature makes a giant leap."</i>

1160
01:08:25,935 --> 01:08:28,169
<i>So, how do theists
explain this sudden outburst</i>

1161
01:08:28,338 --> 01:08:30,638
of new biological information?

1162
01:08:30,807 --> 01:08:33,508
"And God said, 'Let the
water teem with living creatures

1163
01:08:33,676 --> 01:08:35,354
<i>"'and let birds fly
above the earth</i>

1164
01:08:35,378 --> 01:08:37,156
<i>across the expanse of the sky.'</i>

1165
01:08:37,180 --> 01:08:38,824
<i>"So God created the
great creatures of the sea</i>

1166
01:08:38,848 --> 01:08:40,526
<i>"and every living
and moving thing</i>

1167
01:08:40,550 --> 01:08:42,261
<i>"with which the water teems,</i>

1168
01:08:42,285 --> 01:08:43,618
"according to its kind.

1169
01:08:43,786 --> 01:08:49,690
And God saw that it
was good," Genesis 1:20.

1170
01:08:49,859 --> 01:08:51,637
In other words,
creation happened

1171
01:08:51,661 --> 01:08:53,541
because God said
it should happen.

1172
01:08:53,597 --> 01:08:55,357
And even what
looks, to our eyes,

1173
01:08:55,398 --> 01:08:58,833
to be a blind, unguided process

1174
01:08:59,202 --> 01:09:04,472
could really be divinely
controlled from start to finish.

1175
01:09:12,549 --> 01:09:16,651
Isn't there anyone you'd like
to have here with you for this?

1176
01:09:16,819 --> 01:09:22,524
No, there's nobody.

1177
01:09:24,961 --> 01:09:32,961
♪♪♪

1178
01:09:39,976 --> 01:09:47,976
♪♪♪

1179
01:09:54,991 --> 01:09:56,757
♪♪♪

1180
01:09:59,462 --> 01:10:03,931
Lies, lies, and more lies.

1181
01:10:04,301 --> 01:10:06,267
It's easy to dismiss
what you don't understand

1182
01:10:06,436 --> 01:10:08,236
or what you don't
want to understand.

1183
01:10:10,106 --> 01:10:13,908
<i>There it is, the default
setting of the Bible-thumper.</i>

1184
01:10:14,277 --> 01:10:18,346
<i>"If only you would open
the Scripture and read,</i>

1185
01:10:18,515 --> 01:10:21,416
then you would understand."

1186
01:10:21,585 --> 01:10:26,421
So says the brave
young freshman.

1187
01:10:26,590 --> 01:10:32,560
<i>"For thou art wise, and with
thou, all wisdom shall die,"</i>

1188
01:10:32,729 --> 01:10:35,597
<i>Job 12, verse 2.</i>

1189
01:10:35,765 --> 01:10:37,632
What else does Job tell us?

1190
01:10:37,800 --> 01:10:41,402
"For man who is born
of woman is few of days,

1191
01:10:41,571 --> 01:10:42,903
"and full of trouble.

1192
01:10:43,072 --> 01:10:45,773
"He comes forth like a
shadow and does not continue.

1193
01:10:45,942 --> 01:10:49,877
"So man lies down,
and does not rise

1194
01:10:50,046 --> 01:10:53,381
'til the heavens are no more."

1195
01:10:53,550 --> 01:10:59,320
Well, at least he
got that part right.

1196
01:10:59,489 --> 01:11:02,690
What happened to you?

1197
01:11:10,066 --> 01:11:15,570
When a 12-year-old watches
his mother dying of cancer,

1198
01:11:15,739 --> 01:11:19,674
it's only natural to
beg God for her life.

1199
01:11:19,842 --> 01:11:21,776
<i>He'll promise anything</i>

1200
01:11:21,944 --> 01:11:24,512
to his make-believe
grandfather in the sky,

1201
01:11:24,681 --> 01:11:26,759
including to love and
worship him forever,

1202
01:11:26,783 --> 01:11:32,754
if only he will spare her.

1203
01:11:32,922 --> 01:11:35,423
Sometimes the answer is no.

1204
01:11:35,592 --> 01:11:39,026
Tell that to me the day
you lose someone you love.

1205
01:11:39,396 --> 01:11:41,061
<i>She died believing a lie.</i>

1206
01:11:41,431 --> 01:11:43,542
She died believing that
someone out there loved her

1207
01:11:43,566 --> 01:11:47,835
even while he was
strangling her to death.

1208
01:11:48,004 --> 01:11:52,340
A God who would allow
that is not worth believing in.

1209
01:11:52,509 --> 01:11:56,944
That is why,
Wheaton, you will find

1210
01:11:57,113 --> 01:12:02,383
the most committed
atheists were once Christians,

1211
01:12:02,552 --> 01:12:04,497
but we took the blinders off.

1212
01:12:04,521 --> 01:12:08,556
We saw the world
for what it truly is.

1213
01:12:08,725 --> 01:12:12,427
<i>You see, Shakespeare
had it right.</i>

1214
01:12:12,595 --> 01:12:16,664
Life is really a
tale told by an idiot,

1215
01:12:16,833 --> 01:12:22,570
full of sound and fury,
and signifying nothing.

1216
01:12:22,739 --> 01:12:30,739
♪♪♪

1217
01:12:34,884 --> 01:12:36,818
Ayisha!

1218
01:12:36,986 --> 01:12:44,986
♪♪♪

1219
